description: This question will be resolved using event data collected by the Worldwide Integrated Conflict Early Warning System (ICEWS). Data are available at the following links: * Unfiltered ICEWS data (files are named YYYYMMDDHHMMSS.ReleaseXXX_Factiva.csv) * Filtered ICEWS data: 1) armed conflict events per month for all countries and 2) a time series graph filtered for armed conflict events and countries of interest. The question will be resolved using the files from unfiltered ICEWS data for which the filename contains 20190107 through 20190211, inclusive. Within these files, count the event records for which: - ‰Û÷Event Date‰Ûª falls within the period of interest; - ‰Û÷Top Cameo Code‰Ûª is 19; - ‰Û÷Source Country‰Ûª and ‰Û÷Target Country‰Ûª are the countries of interest (in no particular order); - Both ‰Û÷Source Sector‰Ûª and ‰Û÷Target Sector‰Ûª contain the term ‰Û÷Military.‰Ûª These CAMEO codes indicate violent interstate fighting. If a qualifying event is recorded, the question will be closed retroactively with the date of the first event as the end date of the question. This question will be resolved by consulting the data source once each week sometime between 10:00 AM ET Wednesday and 4:00 PM ET Thursday, starting the Wednesday after the question close date and continuing once each week until the data are successfully retrieved. (To download the files, you may have to right-click the Download button and ‰Û÷Save link as...‰Ûª) ICEWS counts are best viewed as a dynamic index of news coverage for a given event/country pair and are most informative when considered in relation to past values for the same country and code(s). ICEWS event data are extracted from the Factiva news database, which draws from a multilingual roster of over 6,000 news sources from around the world. These event data are then assigned event type codes (such as 190 ‰ÛÒ ‰ÛÏUse conventional military force‰Û) based on the Conflict and Mediation Event Observations (CAMEO) codebook. See Chapters 2 and 6 of the CAMEO manual for a detailed codebook and a condensed rundown of event types, respectively.
